MODEL RESEARCH

The objective of this model research is to identify the most suitable Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning (ML) models for developing the AI-Assisted Threat Detection Dashboard. Various cybersecurity notebooks, research papers, and technical resources were studied to understand the performance and suitability of different models for detecting cyber threats.

The models were compared based on their learning type, use case, accuracy, prediction capability, and evaluation metrics such as Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-Score, and ROC-AUC.

During the research, Isolation Forest, Random Forest, XGBoost, Decision Tree, Logistic Regression, One-Class SVM, Local Outlier Factor, and Neural Networks were analyzed for cybersecurity applications such as anomaly detection, intrusion detection, attack classification, and risk prediction.

After comparing these models, Isolation Forest, Random Forest, XGBoost, and Decision Tree were selected because they provide reliable performance and are widely used in cybersecurity systems.

SELECTED MODELS BASED ON RESEARCH

Model	Purpose	Reason for Selection
Isolation Forest	Detect anomalous network activities	Effective for anomaly detection without labeled data
Random Forest	Classify cyber threats	High accuracy and reduces overfitting
XGBoost	Predict threat severity and classify attacks	Excellent prediction performance and high accuracy
Decision Tree	Classify attack types	Simple, fast, and easy to interpret

WHY THESE MODELS WERE CHOSEN

Isolation Forest was selected because it efficiently detects abnormal network behavior and unknown attacks.
Random Forest was chosen due to its high accuracy and reliable threat classification.
XGBoost was selected because it provides excellent predictive performance and helps prioritize security incidents.
Decision Tree was included because it is easy to understand, fast to train, and effective for attack classification.

CONCLUSION

Based on the model research, Isolation Forest, Random Forest, XGBoost, and Decision Tree were identified as the most suitable machine learning models for the AI-Assisted Threat Detection Dashboard. These models provide effective anomaly detection, attack classification, and threat prediction, making them well suited for improving cybersecurity monitoring and incident response.
